modules.name: AWS.WorkMail
modules.comments:
Amazon WorkMail is a secure, managed business email and calendaring service with support for existing desktop and mobile email clients. You can access your email, contacts, and calendars using Microsoft Outlook, your browser, or their native iOS and Android email applications. You can integrate Amazon WorkMail with your existing corporate directory and control both the keys that encrypt your data and the location in which your data is stored.

The Amazon WorkMail API is designed for the following scenarios:

  • Listing and describing organizations

  • Managing users

  • Managing groups

  • Managing resources

All Amazon WorkMail API actions are Amazon-authenticated and certificate-signed. They not only require the use of the AWS SDK, but also allow for the exclusive use of IAM users and roles to help facilitate access, trust, and permission policies. By creating a role and allowing an IAM user to access the Amazon WorkMail site, the IAM user gains full administrative visibility into the entire Amazon WorkMail organization (or as set in the IAM policy). This includes, but is not limited to, the ability to create, update, and delete users, groups, and resources. This allows developers to perform the scenarios listed above, as well as give users the ability to grant access on a selective basis using the IAM model.

declarations.comments: Adds a member to the resource's set of delegates.
declarations.title: associateDelegateToResource

declarations.comments: Adds a member to the group's set.
declarations.title: associateMemberToGroup

declarations.comments: Adds an alias to the set of a given member of Amazon WorkMail.
declarations.title: createAlias

declarations.comments: Creates a group that can be used in Amazon WorkMail by calling the RegisterToWorkMail operation.
declarations.title: createGroup

declarations.comments: Creates a new Amazon WorkMail resource. The available types are equipment and room.
declarations.title: createResource

declarations.comments: Creates a user who can be used in Amazon WorkMail by calling the RegisterToWorkMail operation.
declarations.title: createUser

declarations.comments: Remove the alias from a set of aliases for a given user.
declarations.title: deleteAlias

declarations.comments: Deletes a group from Amazon WorkMail.
declarations.title: deleteGroup

declarations.comments: Deletes the specified resource.
declarations.title: deleteResource

declarations.comments: Deletes a user from Amazon WorkMail and all subsequent systems. The action can't be undone. The mailbox is kept as-is for a minimum of 30 days, without any means to restore it.
declarations.title: deleteUser

declarations.comments: Mark a user, group, or resource as no longer used in Amazon WorkMail. This action disassociates the mailbox and schedules it for clean-up. Amazon WorkMail keeps mailboxes for 30 days before they are permanently removed. The functionality in the console is Disable.
declarations.title: deregisterFromWorkMail

declarations.comments: Returns the data available for the group.
declarations.title: describeGroup

declarations.comments: Provides more information regarding a given organization based on its identifier.
declarations.title: describeOrganization

declarations.comments: Returns the data available for the resource.
declarations.title: describeResource

declarations.comments: Provides information regarding the user.
declarations.title: describeUser

declarations.comments: Removes a member from the resource's set of delegates.
declarations.title: disassociateDelegateFromResource

declarations.comments: Removes a member from a group.
declarations.title: disassociateMemberFromGroup

declarations.comments: Creates a paginated call to list the aliases associated with a given entity.

declarations.comments: Returns an overview of the members of a group.
declarations.title: listGroupMembers

declarations.comments: Returns summaries of the organization's groups.
declarations.title: listGroups

declarations.comments: Returns summaries of the customer's non-deleted organizations.
declarations.title: listOrganizations

declarations.comments: Lists the delegates associated with a resource. Users and groups can be resource delegates and answer requests on behalf of the resource.
declarations.title: listResourceDelegates

declarations.comments: Returns summaries of the organization's resources.
declarations.title: listResources

declarations.comments: Returns summaries of the organization's users.
declarations.title: listUsers

declarations.comments: Registers an existing and disabled user, group, or resource/entity for Amazon WorkMail use by associating a mailbox and calendaring capabilities. It performs no change if the entity is enabled and fails if the entity is deleted. This operation results in the accumulation of costs. For more information, see Pricing. The equivalent console functionality for this operation is Enable. Users can either be created by calling the CreateUser API or they can be synchronized from your directory. For more information, see DeregisterFromWorkMail.
declarations.title: registerToWorkMail

declarations.comments: Allows the administrator to reset the password for a user.
declarations.title: resetPassword

declarations.comments: Updates the primary email for an entity. The current email is moved into the list of aliases (or swapped between an existing alias and the current primary email) and the email provided in the input is promoted as the primary.
declarations.title: updatePrimaryEmailAddress

declarations.comments: Updates data for the resource. It must be preceded by a describe call in order to have the latest information. The dataset in the request should be the one expected when performing another describe call.
declarations.title: updateResource

declarations.comments: At least one delegate must be associated to the resource to disable automatic replies from the resource.
declarations.title: BookingOptions

declarations.comments: The name of the attribute, which is one of the values defined in the UserAttribute enumeration.
